#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:1
msgid "cdylib crates for C interoperability"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.10](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.10-brightgreen.svg) for `rustc`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.11](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.11-brightgreen.svg) for `cargo`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:7
msgid ""
"If you're producing a library that you intend to be used from C (or another "
"language through a C FFI), there's no need for Rust to include Rust-specific "
"stuff in the final object code. For libraries like that, you'll want to use "
"the `cdylib` crate type in your `Cargo.toml`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:12
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[lib]\n"
"crate-type = [\"cdylib\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:17
msgid ""
"This will produce a smaller binary, with no Rust-specific information inside "
"of it."
msgstr ""
